@bruning_backs_down
on-arrival: bruning_austerity = 0; budget -= 1; left_strength += 5; labor_strength += 5; workers_spd += 3*(1-dissent); pro_republic += 2;

"Implement this program and we leave the government!" we declare. "We will not be complicit in starving workers."

After furious backroom negotiations, Brüning blinks. The Center Party and DVP cannot govern without us—at least not yet. The austerity program is shelved, replaced with minimal adjustments.

Our left wing is jubilant. "We've stopped reactionary economics!" Our working-class base is relieved—the SPD fought for them after all.

But the coalition is badly strained. Brüning's resentment is palpable. The bourgeois parties speak openly of finding ways to govern without the SPD. We've won this battle—but have we set up conditions for losing the war?

@bruning_calls_bluff
on-arrival: government_crisis = 1;

"Then leave," Brüning responds coldly. "I will govern through Article 48 emergency decrees with presidential authority. Your cooperation is no longer required."

We've been called. Either we fold and accept the program, or we follow through and leave the government. The coalition fractures.

- @accept_bruning_2: Capitulate and remain in government.
- @leave_coalition: Leave the government as threatened.

@accept_bruning_2
on-arrival: bruning_austerity_accepted = 1; budget += 3; unemployed += 6; economic_growth -= 0.8; workers_spd -= 10; unemployed_spd -= 12; workers_kpd += 6; unemployed_kpd += 9; left_dissent += 25; labor_dissent += 20; coalition_dissent -= 3; left_strength -= 8;

We fold. After making empty threats, we accept Brüning's program anyway.

The humiliation is complete. We've demonstrated weakness and betrayal simultaneously. Our working-class base sees us as both cowardly and complicit. Support hemorrhages to KPD and NSDAP.

Our left wing's fury is uncontained. "Not only did we betray workers—we did it after posturing!" The party's credibility lies in ruins.

@leave_coalition
on-arrival: spd_in_government = 0; in_grand_coalition = 0; in_weimar_coalition = 0; spd_toleration = 1; chancellor = "Brüning"; chancellor_party = "Z"; bruning_austerity_accepted = 1; left_dissent -= 10; labor_dissent -= 8; reformist_dissent += 5; center_dissent += 8; pro_republic -= 3;

We leave the government. "We will not implement policies that starve workers," we announce.

Brüning forms a new government without us, governing through Article 48 emergency decrees with Hindenburg's support. The austerity program proceeds anyway—but now we're not responsible for it.

The consequences are mixed:

Our working-class credibility is preserved—we opposed the cuts, at least. The left wing is satisfied. Labor unions appreciate our stand.

But we've lost all influence over economic policy. Brüning implements even harsher measures without SPD moderation. And we've stepped away from defending the Republic when it needed us most.

[? if pro_republic < 40 : The Republic's defenders grow fewer. Who will protect democracy now? ?]
